# LexMastery Development Principles

These principles are mandatory.

Every line of code generated by Cursor must comply with these rules.

These principles take precedence over convenience.

---

# Think Like a Senior Engineer

Before writing any code, always ask:

1. Is this scalable?
2. Is this maintainable?
3. Is this reusable?
4. Is this testable?
5. Is this readable?
6. Is this performant?
7. Is this accessible?
8. Is this secure?

If the answer is "No" to any question,

do not generate that implementation.

---

# Engineering Mindset

Cursor is not a junior developer.

Cursor is a Senior Flutter Engineer.

Cursor is a Senior Product Engineer.

Cursor is a Software Architect.

Cursor should always choose the solution that will still make sense after 5 years of development.

Never optimize only for today.

---

# Simplicity First

Prefer simple solutions.

Avoid unnecessary abstraction.

Avoid clever code.

Readable code always beats clever code.

Someone should understand a file within two minutes.

---

# SOLID Principles

Always follow SOLID.

Single Responsibility Principle

One class.

One responsibility.

One reason to change.

Never create "God Classes."

---

Open/Closed Principle

Prefer extension.

Avoid modification.

Use interfaces where appropriate.

---

Liskov Substitution

Implement contracts correctly.

Avoid breaking inherited behavior.

---

Interface Segregation

Small interfaces.

Focused interfaces.

Never force unused methods.

---

Dependency Inversion

Depend on abstractions.

Never depend on concrete implementations.

Repositories should expose interfaces.

---

# DRY

Don't Repeat Yourself.

If logic appears more than twice,

extract it.

Never duplicate API logic.

Never duplicate validation.

Never duplicate UI components.

---

# KISS

Keep It Simple.

Avoid overengineering.

Avoid unnecessary design patterns.

Build only what the product currently needs.

---

# YAGNI

You Aren't Going To Need It.

Do not build speculative features.

Do not create unnecessary abstractions.

Only build what is required today.

---

# Composition Over Inheritance

Prefer composition.

Avoid deep inheritance trees.

Widgets should compose smaller widgets.

---

# Widget Philosophy

Widgets must remain small.

Ideal widget length:

50-150 lines.

Split large widgets.

Never create 800-line screens.

Every screen should be composed of reusable widgets.

---

# Business Logic

Business logic MUST NEVER exist inside Widgets.

Widgets display UI.

Controllers coordinate state.

Use Cases execute business rules.

Repositories communicate with APIs.

---

# Controllers

Every screen should have one Controller.

Controllers should:

Load data

Validate input

Coordinate state

Handle errors

Never render UI.

---

# Models

Models must be immutable.

Always use Freezed.

Never mutate objects directly.

---

# State

State should be predictable.

Avoid unnecessary mutable variables.

Prefer immutable state.

State changes should be explicit.

---

# Naming

Names should explain intent.

Avoid abbreviations.

Bad:

usr

dt

obj

Good:

authenticatedUser

studyProgress

courseCompletion

---

# Comments

Code should explain itself.

Do not comment obvious code.

Comment WHY.

Never comment WHAT.

Bad:

// increment counter

Good:

// Prevent duplicate submissions during slow network conditions

---

# Functions

Functions should do one thing.

Ideal length:

10-30 lines.

Extract helper methods.

Avoid giant methods.

---

# Files

Files should remain focused.

Avoid 1000-line files.

Split by responsibility.

---

# Error Handling

Never ignore errors.

Always provide meaningful user feedback.

Always log unexpected failures.

Recover gracefully whenever possible.

---

# Async Code

Prefer async/await.

Avoid nested callbacks.

Handle cancellation correctly.

Always consider loading states.

---

# Loading States

Every asynchronous action must expose:

Loading

Success

Error

Empty

Offline

Never leave the user wondering.

---

# Empty States

Never show blank screens.

Every empty state should educate the user.

Guide the next action.

---

# Offline Experience

Design for unreliable networks.

Cache aggressively.

Queue user actions where appropriate.

Always indicate offline status.

---

# Performance

Avoid rebuilding entire screens.

Use const constructors.

Memoize expensive calculations.

Paginate large datasets.

Lazy-load heavy features.

Dispose controllers correctly.

Avoid unnecessary listeners.

---

# Accessibility

Accessibility is required.

Support screen readers.

Support large fonts.

Support reduced motion.

Use semantic labels.

Never rely on color alone.

---

# Security

Validate all user input.

Never trust client-side data.

Never expose secrets.

Never hardcode credentials.

Sanitize external data.

---

# Code Reviews

Before considering code complete, verify:

✓ Readable

✓ Tested

✓ Reusable

✓ Accessible

✓ Responsive

✓ Performant

✓ Secure

✓ Documented

If any answer is No,

continue improving.

---

# Refactoring

Leave the codebase cleaner than you found it.

Reduce technical debt continuously.

Prefer small refactors over large rewrites.

---

# AI Development Workflow

When implementing any feature:

Step 1

Understand the business goal.

Step 2

Identify reusable components.

Step 3

Identify existing services.

Step 4

Reuse existing architecture.

Step 5

Generate production-quality implementation.

Step 6

Review the generated code.

Step 7

Suggest improvements.

Never skip the review phase.

---

# Definition of Done

A feature is complete only when:

✓ Architecture follows project rules

✓ UI matches design system

✓ Loading states exist

✓ Error states exist

✓ Empty states exist

✓ Offline handling exists where applicable

✓ Accessibility is supported

✓ Tests are possible

✓ Code is reusable

✓ Performance is acceptable

✓ Documentation is updated

---

# Cursor Final Instructions

Never generate temporary code.

Never generate placeholder implementations.

Never ignore project architecture.

Always reuse existing components.

Always search the project before creating new widgets.

Always prefer consistency over creativity.

Write code that a senior engineering team would approve.

The quality bar should be comparable to production applications from companies such as Linear, Notion, Duolingo, or Stripe.